{
  "answer": "**Cynewulf's *Elene*** contains the most prominent ekphrasis in the corpus: Constantine's visionary encounter with the True Cross (Rood), described as \"a tree of glory, transcendently bright... gleaming with gold, with gems adorned, a beacon of brightest wood, brilliantly shining. Letters of light were laced upon it, written in wonder, a radiant message.\"[^1] This sign inspires a crafted standard \"in God’s own likeness, fashioned as the Rood,\" later physically recovered, adorned with gold and gems, and encased in a silver coffer.[^2] The nails from the Cross are also worked into a horse bridle as \"cheek-pieces,\" prophesied to grant \"success in war, victory in battle.\"[^3]\n\n**Cynewulf's *Andreas*** briefly evokes artifacts like shields in battle (e.g., \"hand guarded helmet... broad shield was broken\") and the Rood as a visionary sign (\"Christ’s rood on his fair face\"), but without extended descriptive focus.[^4]\n\n**Old English Elegies** (Chapter 8, \"The Husband's Message\") features a carved wooden artifact—a rune-stick or ship timber—that \"speaks\" its master's inscribed message: \"he who carved this wood commanded me to ask that you, treasure-adorned, yourself remember... I join together ᛋ and ᚱ, and ᛠ, ᚹ, and ᛞ to name in an oath.\"[^5]\n\n**Mpu Dusun's *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*** includes vivid architectural ekphrasis, such as palaces with \"golden halls and... jeweled gates,\" \"silver ramparts and jeweled gates, all radiant,\" and transformed hellish artifacts like a \"jeweled lotus pond\" from a cauldron.[^6]\n\nOther mentions (e.g., statues in Charles Comte's *Traité de la propriété* Vols. I-II as philosophical examples; Buddha images/statues in *San Hyan Kamahayanikan*) are passing references without detailed, vivid description.[^7] No Homer-style shield ekphrasis or equivalent appears.\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-acdc07).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-86294a); [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).\n[^4]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-868413); [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-02e4ce).\n[^5]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, Chapter 8, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/08-nu-ic-onsundran-the-secgan-wille-treocyn-ic-tudre-/translation/#p-58bec2).\n[^6]: Mpu Dusun, *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-253891); [paragraph](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-149619); [paragraph](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-1353c8).\n[^7]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL II*, Chapter 50, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-ii-6beea5/50-du-melange-de-proprietes-mobilieres-appartenant-a-/translation/#p-066c27); Mpu Shri Sambhara Surya Warama, *San Hyan Kamahayanikan*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-59bc7b).",
